Great! Here’s a step-by-step guide to help you host your website online using GitHub Pages (a free and reliable option). Follow these steps:

Step 1: Create a GitHub Account

  1. Go to GitHub and create an account (if you don’t already have one).
  2. Once registered, log in.

Step 2: Create a Repository

  1. After logging in, click on the + sign in the top-right corner and select New Repository.
  2. Name the repository something like amritesh-website.
  3. Make it Public and check the box that says Add a README file.
  4. Click Create Repository.

Step 3: Upload Your Website Files

  1. On the repository page, click on Add file > Upload files.
  2. Drag and drop the HTML file you just created into the upload area.
  3. If you have additional files like images, CSS, or JavaScript, upload those as well.
  4. Click Commit changes to save your files to the repository.

Step 4: Enable GitHub Pages

  1. Go to the Settings tab of your repository.
  2. Scroll down to the Pages section in the left-hand menu.
  3. Under Source, select the branch as main (or master).
  4. Click Save.
  5. GitHub will generate a URL for your website, such as:
    https://<your-username>.github.io/amritesh-website

Step 5: Test Your Website

  1. Open the provided URL in your browser.
  2. Your website should now be live! 🎉

Optional: Customize Your Website Further

  • If you want to modify or update your website, edit the files in your repository and commit the changes.
  • You can also add a custom domain name (e.g., www.amritesh.com). For this, you’ll need to purchase a domain and configure DNS settings in GitHub Pages.

Let me know if you face any issues, or if you’d prefer help with using another platform like Netlify or Vercel for hosting!
